<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="51" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="51">
<pageBreakToken pageId="12" pageNumber="51" start="start">Discussion</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="51">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saerkinen &amp; P. Gonzales" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum arenicola" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arenicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum arenicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum americanum" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="americanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum americanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Mill., the only other similar Morelloid species found in lowland Amazonia; it has larger anthers which are 3.0-3.2 mm long in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saerkinen &amp; P. Gonzales" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum arenicola" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arenicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum arenicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as compared to the minute anthers &lt;1.5 mm of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum americanum" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="americanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum americanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Specimens without locality information can be easily confused with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum nigrescens" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nigrescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum nigrescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
M.Martens &amp; Galeotti of Central and northern South America, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dun" authorityYear="1852" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum aloysiifolium" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aloysiifolium">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum aloysiifolium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dunal of middle to high elevation Argentina and Bolivia or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bitter" authorityYear="1912" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum subtusviolaceum" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subtusviolaceum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum subtusviolaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bitter of low to middle elevation Peru and Bolivia. Both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saerkinen &amp; P. Gonzales" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum arenicola" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arenicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum arenicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum nigrescens" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nigrescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum nigrescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have simple inflorescences, but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saerkinen &amp; P. Gonzales" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum arenicola" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arenicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum arenicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in having longer anthers (3.0-3.2 mm) compared to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum nigrescens" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nigrescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum nigrescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(1.5-2.2 mm) and in the possession of glandular hairs (
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum nigrescens" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nigrescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum nigrescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is eglandular). The anthers are similar in size and shape to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dun" authorityYear="1852" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum aloysiifolium" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aloysiifolium">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum aloysiifolium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saerkinen &amp; P. Gonzales" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum arenicola" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arenicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum arenicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has simple inflorescences and glandular-tipped hairs, while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dun" authorityYear="1852" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum aloysiifolium" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aloysiifolium">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum aloysiifolium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has branched inflorescences (sometimes many branched) and lacks glandular hairs. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bitter" authorityYear="1912" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum subtusviolaceum" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subtusviolaceum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum subtusviolaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
possesses the same dense, glandular-haired indumentum as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saerkinen &amp; P. Gonzales" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum arenicola" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arenicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum arenicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs from it in having inflorescences with the flowers clustered near the tips positioned opposite the leaves rather than arising along the internodes, longer calyx lobes (2-3 mm versus 0.2-0.5 mm), more rotate corollas lobed only halfway to the base, and less exerted styles (to a maximum of 1 mm versus exerted to 3 mm beyond the anther cone).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="51">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saerkinen &amp; P. Gonzales" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum arenicola" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arenicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum arenicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the few morelloids known from lowland humid forests in South America. Most morelloid species grow&gt; 2,000 m or in drier habitats along the western slope of the Andes or in the inter-Andean valleys, whilst 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saerkinen &amp; P. Gonzales" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum arenicola" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arenicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum arenicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted to humid forests on the eastern side of the Andes below 1,200 m elevation. Currently, the species is known from central and southern Peru and from Bolivia, but it is likely that the species also occurs in adjacent areas of Brazil in the state of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Rondônia">Rondonia</normalizedToken>
, where the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
Madre de Dios and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
Beni join and cross the Brazilian border, especially considering habitat preferences of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saerkinen &amp; P. Gonzales" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum arenicola" order="Solanales" pageId="12" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arenicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="51">Solanum arenicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for disturbed, sandy soils along river banks.
</paragraph>
